ce:section.ce:para:
Cytotoxicity was an essential factor in determining the safety of biomaterials. Therefore, before Mg-N-CQDs were used in biological experiments, the toxicity of Mg-N-CQDs was determined by the CCK-8 method. In this study, HeLa cells were used to study the cytotoxicity of Mg-N-CQDs. HeLa cells were cultured in 8 concentration gradients. The results showed that 0.05 mg/ml of Mg-N-CQDs was the most favorable concentration for seedling growth. When the concentration of Mg-N-CQDs reached 0.8 mg/ml, the cell survival rate was still above 85%, indicating that Mg-N-CQDs had no apparent cytotoxicity and could be used in subsequent biological experiments (Text S2 and 
                           Fig. S3
                        ). Besides, the root length, plant height, number of roots and fresh weight of wheat seeds were used as evaluation indicators to analyze the effects of N, P, K combined with Mg-N-CQDs fertilization on the growth characteristics of wheat. The results showed that the root length, plant height, root number, and fresh weight of wheat seedlings with different fertilization ratios were significantly increased compared with the control group, indicating that 0.8 mg/ml Mg-N-CQDs was a safe and effective dosage, which had no biological toxicity to wheat seedlings (
                           Fig. S4
                        ), indicating that Mg-N-CQDs could be applied to plant nutrient solution together with N, P, K, and other fertilizers. Therefore, it was also verified that N, P, K, and other fertilizers can synergistically promote the growth of seedlings with Mg-N-CQDs without negative interference effects.

Furthermore, the dry matter weight per plant of wheat treated with UV-A decreased significantly (
                           Table S2
                        ). The decrease in dry matter may be because UV-B caused the blocking of chlorophyll photosynthetic production, which would be confirmed by experiments later. In addition, the content of chlorophyll and flavonoids were commonly used indicators to study the impact of UV-B on plants. The impact of UV-B on wheat chlorophyll content was significantly more significant than that of flavonoids. The possible reason was that flavonoids had a strong absorption effect on UV-B. One indicator of the impact of UV-B on plants was a decrease in chlorophyll content, and flavonoids were a mechanism by which plants adapt to UV-B. Therefore, chlorophyll should be used to indicate the degree of damage to plants caused by UV-B.

ROS was a chemical marker predicting UV-B tolerance to plant stress. Oxidative stress occurs as the balance between ROS and antioxidant defenses is disrupted, specifically changed in the activities of antioxidant enzymes such as catalase (CAT), superoxide dismutase (SOD), and peroxidase (POD) in plant seedlings. Therefore, UV-B radiation indirectly affects the physiological response of plants by affecting the synthesis of secondary metabolites, which may affect physiological phenomena such as plant growth, biomass, photosynthetic system, and antioxidant system, resulting in cell damage. Since they have a limited ability to resist oxidative stress and a fixed lifestyle, plants cannot avoid long-term solar UV-B radiation. They cannot move as freely as animals, which requires the help of antioxidants for phytoremediation. Based on the highly designable structure of CQDs, the edge of the absorption band in the visible light region was expanded by introducing chromophores such as amino and hydroxyl groups into CQDs because –NH and –OH can enhance the electron transfer from the excited organic unit to the metal–oxygen cluster, and the ability of the metal–oxygen cluster to be directly excited, thus expanding the light absorption edge of CQDs from the ultraviolet light region to the visible light region [10]. In this study, CQDs doped with appropriate concentrations of metal oxides (Mg-N-CQDs) positively affected plant growth and development, mainly promoting plant root and callus growth and enhancing plant biological quantity. Specifically, it increases biomass accumulation, promotes root growth, and increases total chlorophyll content and antioxidant enzyme activity. The process of alleviating UV-B damage to wheat seedlings by Mg-N-CQDs was shown in Fig. 6 , which demonstrated that Mg-N-CQDs with small particle sizes were effective antioxidants, which could activate the antioxidant system of wheat seedlings, effectively increase superoxide dismutase (SOD), catalase (CAT) and peroxidase (POD) to eliminate malondialdehyde (MDA), hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and superoxide anion (O2 −) on the roots and cells, preventing seedlings from being damaged by UV-B stress oxidation, validating Mg-N-CQDs can alleviate the stress and possible biotoxicity of UV-B radiation as a sunscreen for wheat seedlings. Therefore, chromophore functions such as amino and hydroxyl groups and Mg, N modified CQDs could broaden the light absorption range of CQDs and improve the ability to convert blue light and ultraviolet rays to visible light (
Fig. S8
), which was the main reason why Mg-N-CQDs could relieve wheat seedlings from ultraviolet stress.
